  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a global consensus that money laundering is against the law.\n\nHere's why:\n\n*   **International Conventions:** The United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988) and the UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000) are key international treaties that require signatory countries to criminalize money laundering. Almost all countries are party to these conventions.\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF):** The FATF is an inter-governmental body that sets international standards to combat money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system. Its recommendations are widely adopted by countries worldwide.\n*   **National Laws:** Virtually every country has enacted laws to prohibit money laundering. These laws typically make it a criminal offense to conceal or disguise the proceeds of crime, to use or possess such proceeds, or to assist others in doing so.\n*   **Public Policy:** Money laundering facilitates criminal activity and undermines the integrity of financial systems. Governments around the world recognize the need to combat it.\n\nTherefore, based on international conventions, the efforts of organizations like the FATF, and the national laws of almost every country, there is a clear and widespread consensus that money laundering is illegal.",
